(I use Apple devices very often. Overall, I like macOS. Certainly more than Windows. One of the) Tj
T*
(things I find extremely useful is a command I discovered not too long ago: pbcopy . pbcopy can) Tj
T*
(be used to copy to the clipboard whatever it receives from standard input. For example, when I) Tj
T*
(am in a shell, I often use a command like this: cat filename.md | pbcopy At that point I know) Tj
T*
(that the content of the file is in the clipboard, and I can paste it wherever I need, calmly) Tj
T*
(and without any additional steps. There is one limitation, though: this only works locally. It) Tj
T*
(works when I am using my Mac and I want to copy something from the macOS shell. When I connect) Tj
T*
(to a remote \(*BSD, Linux, illumos based\) server via ssh, pbcopy is not available. Or, more) Tj
T*
(precisely, even if I create a command with the same name on the server, that command cannot) Tj
T*
(directly talk to the clipboard of my Mac in the usual way. Luckily, modern terminal emulators) Tj
T*
(have a few tricks available. I use iTerm2 for most of my ssh sessions and, once I realised how) Tj
T*
(useful it would be to have something similar to pbcopy in remote sessions too, I created a) Tj
T*
(small script that works both on Linux, the BSDs and illumox based OSes. Th...) Tj
